1. Take the Longest View in the Room
Taking the longest view in the room means acquiring underpriced assets and =
building underappreciated capabilities today knowing that they=E2=80=99ll p=
ay off far in the future, when it=E2=80=99s too late for everyone else to c=
atch up. It=E2=80=99s the most important lesson, because the long view unlo=
cks all of the other moves we=E2=80=99ll discuss.=20
My favorite companies take the longest views. Amazon, Snap, Slack, Spotify,=
 Stripe. In Stripe: The Internet=E2=80=99s Most Undervalued Company [https:=
//email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkMtqxDAMRb9mvEvwK61n4cVs-hvBD2VixrGDLU9Jv75u=
BloKEgJdpCNdZxDuuRx6zxVJq1Dm4DV740pM8kq8lp6pSZFQ56UAbCZEjaUB2ZuNwRkMOZ0TlPK=
JrFo6w6mw4iqVVUy--0VRu4DiZhGGS09-OLNpPkByoOEJ5cgJSNQr4l4v4nbhHz1SRptLSPexNl=
vRuMfo8taFvWfFEnYYcIUhJISSAOuw9cVDSx7K08QGfgAnSNCccsoY5UxMnIuRjbE1kPIL83qRd=
LvzfwBS9C-5y4_VbBBPof8797q1FPCYIRkbwb-swJd552d47KATfNYI2C97NU9HlZBXqkin-dxt=
TH-gbzRahwc], I quoted Stripe CEO Patrick Collison, who said of Amazon=E2=
=80=99s Jeff Bezos:
There=E2=80=99s something quite deep about the notion of using time horizon=
s as a competitive advantage, in that you=E2=80=99re simply willing to wait=
 longer than other people and you have an organization that is thusly orien=
ted.
Taking the longest view in the room shifts the field of play. As Hinkie wro=
te, =E2=80=9Cto take the long view has an unintuitive advantage built in=E2=
=80=94fewer competitors.=E2=80=9D Everybody is trying to sign LeBron James =
today; very few teams are trying to build up the assets that might give the=
m a chance to draft the next LeBron James in five years. Everyone wants to =
buy customers via Google and Facebook ads today; very few companies built p=
roprietary growth channels five years ago that are paying off today. Less d=
emand means that those assets are relatively underpriced.=20
Hinkie also uses Bezos as his example of someone willing to take the long v=
iew, writing, =E2=80=9CJeff Bezos says that if Amazon has a good quarter it=
=E2=80=99s because of work they did 3, 4, 5 years ago=E2=80=94not because t=
hey did a good job that quarter.=E2=80=9D
Taking the longest view in the room is also just mathematically advantageou=
s. In his book, The Psychology of Money [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/e=
JxFkLtuxCAQRb9m6WwBBpstKNKki5QivcVjYqNgsHjE8n59WG8RaTSjeVwdzTWqwBLTKfeYC6oZ=
0uysJCMVA2d3ZCWzRHCBXJ6_E8CmnJclVUB71d4ZVVwMlwJjytEqgQ8gtLBsHCkejdaTHqdJGGM=
4H5ky6MmZVbUOggEJv5DOGAB5uZay59vwdqPvLY7j6NWmHjH0Jm5t8JlPs0Yfl7P7aIKz-3IbeM=
i5e6YYcreqfXehNe3a7i1hwSdyn0ZBkJMUU0wIpmTglA496X2twNijxPXG8LbQPledizI_TyBKM=
sSiY3JhaeufVTXYtWh_z61uNbhyzhCU9mBflpSXideH5dxBBjiyh1IgvYaXs2JgdyxQo9nY7Az_=
oD9Biof6], Morgan Housel illustrates the power of time as clearly as I=E2=
=80=99ve ever seen. He points out that much of Warren Buffett=E2=80=99s suc=
cess is due to the fact that he=E2=80=99s been compounding money since he w=
as 10, and is still doing it at 90. If he had retired at 60, he=E2=80=99d b=
e worth $11.9 million, not $84.5 billion that 30 extra years of compounding=
 at 22% earned him. If RenTech=E2=80=99s Jim Simons had earned his 66% annu=
al returns for as long as Buffett, he would be worth sixty-three quintillio=
n nine hundred quadrillion seven hundred eighty-one trillion seven hundred =
eighty billion seven hundred forty-eight million one hundred sixty thousand=
 dollars. Compounding, man.=20
Worldbuilders take the longest view in the room. They know that to build en=
during advantages, they have to accumulate small, non-obvious advantages ov=
er time that compound into an unimpeachable competitive position by the tim=
e that everyone else catches up.=20
